\f0\fs21\fsmilli10667 In this section we provide details concerning the dataset and the research methodology employed to empirically verify whether Zipf\'92s law holds for the distribution of cities in poland. For the purpose of this verification, we use population data from the results of the National Census conducted in 2011 by the polish Central Statistical Office 
\f1 \cf2 (CSO, 2011)
\f0 \cf2 .
\fs13\fsmilli6667 \cf2 \up8  
\fs21\fsmilli10667 \cf2 \up0 the CSO database shows the population of different administrative units, from voivodeships to the smallest entities called 
\i \cf2 gmina 
\i0 \cf2 (communities).
\f2\fs24 \

\f0\fs21\fsmilli10667 the 
\i \cf2 gmina 
\i0 \cf2 is the principal unit of administrative division of poland. there are three types of 
\i \cf2 gmina 
\i0 \cf2 \'96 urban, which consists of one city or town; urban-rural, which consists of a town and the surrounding villages; and rural, which consists only of villages and countryside. the size of 
\i \cf2 gminas 
\i0 \cf2 can vary. the largest urban 
\i \cf2 gmina 
\i0 \cf2 is Warsaw, the capital of poland with almost 2 million inhabitants, while the smallest urban 
\i \cf2 gmina 
\i0 \cf2 is Krynica morska with as few as just over a thousand inhabitants. 
\f2\fs24 \

\f0\fs21\fsmilli10667 In our benchmark empirical test, we use only urban communities, giving us 306 observations. However, it has often been argued in the literature that estimation results might be affected by the choice of the unit of analysis (
\f1 \cf2 Berry and Okulicz-Kozaryn, 2011; Modica, 2014; and Veneri, 2016
\f0 \cf2 ). therefore, for the sensitivity analysis we extend the baseline sample by adding the municipal part of the urban-rural communities. 
\f2\fs24 \

\f0\fs21\fsmilli10667 the resulting extended sample has 908 observations and is almost three times larger than the baseline for urban communities alone. the extended sample is, to our best knowledge, the largest dataset used to date in validating Zipf\'92s law for poland. Figure 1 provides an initial insight into the distribution of the population of polish cities. 
\f2\fs24 \

\f0\fs21\fsmilli10667 as indicated above, we estimate the Zipf\'92s regression for the two samples \'96 baseline and extended \'96 in order to use all available information on polish cities. However, there is an intense debate in the literature on the threshold that should be used in verifying Zipf\'92s law (see 
\f1 \cf2 Nitsch 2005
\f0 \cf2 ). For example, as noted by 
\f1 \cf2 Eeckhout (2004)
\f0 \cf2 , the estimation of the Zipf\'92s coefficient decreases with the truncation point. the way to define the right truncation point was discussed in recent studies by 
\f1 \cf2 Bee et al. (2013), Ioannides and Skouras (2013), and Fazio and Modica (2015)
\f0 \cf2 , who proposed different possible criteria for choosing where to draw the cut-off line for the sample of cities that should be included in the empirical analysis. 
\f2\fs24 \

\f0\fs21\fsmilli10667 In order to take these issues into account in our empirical study, we also apply a certain reasonable threshold and estimate the regression in order to be as close as possible to the strict version of Zipf\'92s law. However, in contrast to the aforementioned studies, in our empirical approach we adjust the cut-off somewhat to the result we would like to obtain, in order to see the threshold under which the desired outcome can be reached. 
\f2\fs24 \

\f0\fs21\fsmilli10667 In addition, in some of our regressions for the baseline and extended samples, we also exclude Warsaw from the dataset, since some authors claim that Zipf\'92s law may not hold due to the fact that the largest city in many countries is much larger than would be predicted by the Zipf\'92s distribution. 
\f2\fs24 \

